<a name="coap"></a>
<h2><a name="TOC-The-characteristics-of-a-project"></a>The characteristics of a project</h2>
<h3><a name="TOC-CHANGE"></a><span style="background-color:transparent;font-size:1em;line-height:1.5">CHANGE</span></h3>
<div>Projects are the way organisations introduce change. A change means an understanding of how-it-is-now and how-it-will-be. The project moves the organisation<br />
<h3><a name="TOC-TEMPORARY"></a><span style="background-color:transparent;font-size:1em;line-height:1.5">TEMPORARY</span></h3>
This is different to business-as-usual and people may take on temporary roles and responsibilities. A project should have a defined start and a defined end.</div>
<div>
<h3><a name="TOC-CROSS-FUNCTIONAL"></a><span style="background-color:transparent;font-size:1em;line-height:1.5">CROSS-FUNCTIONAL</span></h3>
<span style="background-color:transparent;font-size:1em;line-height:1.5">Projects involve people with different skills and motivations working together. People from different departments in an organisation work together and this requires communication and organisation.</span></div>
<div>
<h3><a name="TOC-UNIQUE"></a><span style="background-color:transparent;font-size:1em;line-height:1.5">UNIQUE</span></h3>
<span style="background-color:transparent;font-size:1em;line-height:1.5">Every project is, in some way, unique and everyone involved needs to focus on the product and challenges of this project and be prepared to learn and adapt.</span></div>
<h3><a name="TOC-UNCERTAINTY"></a><span style="background-color:transparent;font-size:1em;line-height:1.5">UNCERTAINTY</span></h3>
<div>Projects are inherently more risky than business-as-usual. Project members need to respond to unexpected events. Can risk be reduced? Can it be quantified?</div>
